<tr id="L42"><td><a href="#L42">42</a></td><td>KIRK:  Bones, what do you make of it?</td></tr>

<tr id="L43"><td><a href="#L43">43</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Well, I can't give you any specific circumstance that will explain him.</td></tr>

<tr id="L44"><td><a href="#L44">44</a></td><td>KIRK:  And judging by looking at him, we know at the very least he is the result of a very dramatic conflict. Spock?</td></tr>

<tr id="L45"><td><a href="#L45">45</a></td><td>SPOCK:  There is no theory, Captain, from the basic work of Mendel to recent nucleotide studies, which would explain our captive. All gradations of colour from black to brown, to yellow to white are genetically predictable. We must therefore conclude that this alien is that often unaccountable rarity, a mutation, one of a kind.</td></tr>

<tr id="L46"><td><a href="#L46">46</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Yes, I would agree. That's the case here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L47"><td><a href="#L47">47</a></td><td>KIRK:  Your prognosis, Doctor?</td></tr>

<tr id="L48"><td><a href="#L48">48</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Well, I can't give you one, Jim. I've never worked on anyone like him or anything like him.</td></tr>

<tr id="L49"><td><a href="#L49">49</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Yet you are pumping him full of your noxious potions as if he were a human.</td></tr>

<tr id="L50"><td><a href="#L50">50</a></td><td>MCCOY:  When in doubt, the book prevails, Mister Spock. I've run tests. Blood is blood, even when it's green like yours. The organs are there. They're rearranged to a degree, plus a few I've never seen before. Now, I've enriched the oxygen content of his blood and pumped in a strong stimulant. And I must say his recuperative powers appear to be excellent.</td></tr>

<tr id="L51"><td><a href="#L51">51</a></td><td>SPOCK:  With your permission, Captain, I shall do some further research and join you on the bridge.</td></tr>

